<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LAGUNA BEACH; PLANNING PANEL OKS BREWERY INSTALLATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Plans to install a small brewery in a historic building in the downtown area 
have been unanimously approved by the Planning Commission. 
</P>
<P>
 The unusual new business -- the first of its kind in this city -- will be 
installed in a 60-year-old "Heisler Building" on South Coast Highway, which 
also houses the Jolly Roger restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
 The new Laguna Beach Brewing Co. will feature two-story fermenting tanks at 
the back of the building and an upstairs "brew pub" in the space where the Sail 
Loft was previously located. Patrons will be able to watch as barley and hops 
are transformed into lager and ale. 
</P>
<P>
 "It is an interesting use, (and) it's going to be wildly successful," said 
Planning Commissioner Norm Grossman, who with his colleagues endorsed the 
project last week. "They really have no competition. When you look at some uses 
and see there's an opening in the market, this seems to be one of those." 
</P>
<P>
 The beer will not be bottled to go since Laguna Beach has a law restricting 
the sale of alcohol for off-site consumption within 200 yards of Main Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 The owners of the new business, who for the past year and a half also have 
operated the Huntington Beach Beer Co. near that city's pier, say they hope to 
open in Laguna Beach on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're really excited about coming to Laguna," said architect Jeff Bergsma, 
who is starting the business with his partners Michael Fein and Peter Andreit. 
"We think that the people in Laguna will be the kind of people who would enjoy 
a hand-crafted beer, and we like being in beach cities." 
</P>
<P>
 As a condition of approval, planning commissioners instructed the business 
owners to install equipment to ensure that the odor of hops doesn't leak into 
the air and annoy neighbors. 
</P>
<P>
 They also will restore the 11,082-square-foot building, which is listed on the 
city's Historic Register with the highest rating due to its historical 
significance. 
</P>
<P>
 "The E-rated provincial revival building contributes greatly to the quality of 
downtown Laguna," city staff member Ann Larson said. "It's in excellent 
condition and is a prime historic architectural example." LESLIE EARNEST 
</P>
</TEXT>
