</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two Rival Stock Exchanges Unified: Ending three decades of rivalry that 
stifled trade, the Philippines completed the long-delayed electronic 
unification of its two stock exchanges.The Manila and Makati floors continue to 
trade at separate locations in the capital, but each transaction is now matched 
by a computer link, and standardized share prices are listed under the new 
Philippine Stock Exchange. Exchange executives said the merger, which had been 
delayed for more than a year because of political disputes and technical 
problems, will simplify trading and boost foreign investment. Japanese mutual 
fund investors and brokers have already indicated they will invest additional 
funds in the Philippines once the unification was completed. 
