<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEART ATTACK CLAIMS CIF'S FAGANS AT 84 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Kenneth J. Fagans, a longtime commissioner of the organization that oversees 
Southern California high school sports, died of a heart attack Saturday at Hoag 
Hospital in Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 Fagans, a 30-year resident of Balboa Island, was 84. 
</P>
<P>
 He was the commissioner of the California Interscholastic Federation Southern 
Section office from 1951 until he retired in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
 In his time, the Southern Section grew from 218 to more than 458 high schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Fagans was born in Detroit in 1909 and moved to California with his family in 
1923. 
</P>
<P>
 He was a standout basketball player at Huntington Park High School and earned 
all-state honors as a senior center in 1927. Huntington Park won a Southern 
Section title that year. 
</P>
<P>
 Fagans went to Oregon State, where he was the leading scorer on the freshman 
team. For the next three seasons, he played in every varsity game. Fagans was 
president of his senior class in 1932 at Oregon State. 
</P>
<P>
 Fagans coached basketball at Compton High School from 1947 to 1953. He led his 
team to two Southern Section titles and his teams won 53 consecutive games 
between 1950 and 1953. 
</P>
<P>
 He is survived by Norma, his wife of 52 years, two sons and his sister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
