<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECRUITING / JEFF FELLENZER: UCLA'S REES MAKES UNEXPECTED MOVE TO NFL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF FELLENZER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A funny thing happened to former UCLA assistant football coach Bill Rees 
recently on his way to Lawrence, Kan., to begin a new job as recruiting 
coordinator at Kansas: He wound up back home in Manhattan Beach as the new West 
Coast scout for the Kansas City Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
 After 15 years as the architect of UCLA's nationally recognized football 
recruiting success, Rees, a Chicago native, had agreed to take a similar 
position at Kansas. He booked a flight to Kansas City for Sunday, March 17, and 
was set to begin his new job the next day. Then, just before leaving his office 
at UCLA for the final time March 15, the Chiefs called and Rees fulfilled a 
goal of working for a National Football League team. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to establishing the Bruins as a recruiting power, regularly 
competing for (and signing) players against Notre Dame, Michigan, Ohio State 
and Texas, Rees was in charge of all in-state evaluations for the program. 
Before the start of last season, more players from UCLA appeared on NFL rosters 
(38) than from any other school in the country. 
</P>
<P>
 Among current NFL players Rees signed during his tenure at UCLA were Troy 
Aikman and Frank Cornish (Dallas), Mike Lodish (Buffalo), Eric Ball 
(Cincinnati), Carlton Gray (Seattle), David Richards (Detroit), Kevin Williams 
(Green Bay), plus former pros Mel and Mike Farr and a probable first-round 
draft choice from the current Bruin roster, junior tackle Jonathan Ogden. 
</P>
<P>
 Rees said the rules changes adopted by the NCAA in recent years to limit 
recruiting and the evaluation process has limited the ability of college 
football coaches to make accurate judgments before signing players. There are 
tighter restrictions on in-person evaluations, telephone calls and campus 
visits. Thus, most recruiting coordinators now spend more time watching game 
film than games. It is the games -- the UCLA games, that is -- that Rees will 
miss most. 
</P>
<P>
 "UCLA was always a dream school to be associated with," Rees said. "I was 
fortunate to be part of perhaps the best era in UCLA football history, with an 
opportunity to work for one of the great coaches in college football, Terry 
Donahue. 
</P>
<P>
 "What I'll miss most is the UCLA-USC rivalry -- the great games, the great 
players, the intensity and the atmosphere. It's the best rivalry in the 
country." Notes 
</P>
<P>
 UCLA has completed its football recruiting with the signing of cornerback 
Aaron Roques (6-0, 180). Roques was a standout at Canyon Springs High in Moreno 
Valley three years ago, attracting attention from a number of colleges, 
including UCLA, before he signed a letter of intent with Nevada. However, he 
opted for professional baseball instead of college football. Last year, Roques, 
an outfielder, hit .165 in 32 games for Peoria, Ariz., a rookie league team in 
the San Diego Padres' organization. Before signing with UCLA, Roques turned 
down scholarship offers from California, San Diego State and Nevada Las Vegas, 
among others. The Bruins' incoming class now totals 18 players, including two 
community college transfers. 
</P>
<P>
 Hoop report: Jelani Gardner, Bellflower St. John Bosco's heavily recruited 6-6 
point guard, will announce his college choice April 15, two days after the 
spring signing period begins. Gardner has narrowed his list to three schools: 
UCLA, Arkansas and Cal. He leaves Tuesday for New York, where he will play in 
the McDonald's All-American high school basketball game Sunday at St. John's 
University. Gardner was one of two California players selected for the game; 
the other was Duke signee Rick Price, a 6-5 guard from Gardena Serra. Gardner 
and Price will also play in Magic Johnson's high school all-star game April 10 
in Auburn Hills, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 Add UCLA: The Bruins are also recruiting two other standout players: Brandon 
Jessie, the 6-5, 215-pound forward from Edison High and Ventura College who was 
voted the California community college co-player of the year, and Jerod Ward, a 
6-8 forward from Clinton, Miss., who is the consensus choice among coaches and 
talent evaluators as the nation's No. 1 prospect. Jessie is considering Duke, 
Arizona State, Georgetown, Nevada Las Vegas and UCLA. Ward, a shooter with 
unlimited range, took an unofficial trip to Mississippi last weekend. He has 
also visited UCLA (his cousin, Annett Buckner, plays volleyball for the Bruins) 
and Cal, and taken another unofficial trip to Ohio State (he has relatives in 
that area, too). In addition, Ward may visit Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
 USC, with two scholarships available, is hoping to sign 6-6 swingman Joe 
Zaletel, an excellent shooter from El Camino College who averaged 28.2 points 
last season, second-best in the state behind Darryle Flicking (29.4) of 
Riverside. Zaletel, a sophomore from Torrance High who also attended Harbor 
College, has visited USC and Arizona State, and may take trips to Hawaii and 
Washington State. Kansas has also expressed some interest in Zaletel . . . Add 
Kansas: The Jayhawks, who tried hard to get Price before he signed with Duke, 
have received a verbal commitment from 6-4 guard Billy Thomas of Shreveport, 
La. 
</P>
<P>
 Another community college standout, 6-4 shooting guard Tes Whitlock of 
Saddleback, is considering New Mexico State, Long Beach State and Pepperdine, 
among others. Whitlock, from Loara High, played one season at Arizona State 
before he encountered academic difficulties and transferred. 
</P>
<P>
 Two of the top high school guard prospects in Southern California, 6-3 Jamie 
Gillin of Compton Dominguez and 6-1 Paul Pickett of Wilmington Banning, may be 
close to announcing their college choices. Gillin will probably sign with 
Washington State, while Pickett, if he qualifies academically, will likely 
attend George Mason University in Fairfax, Va., which is coached by former 
Lakers and Loyola Marymount Coach Paul Westhead. Another Southland guard, 6-1 
Sam Turks of Inglewood, recently gave a verbal commitment to Utah. 
</P>
<P>
 Add Pac-10: Cal Coach Todd Bozeman's reputation as a recruiter continues to 
grow. Bozeman has apparently persuaded 6-11 center-forward Eric Lee of 
Indianola, Miss., to take a recruiting trip to Berkeley. Lee made a verbal 
commitment in January to Nevada Las Vegas, but is reconsidering his decision 
and might also visit Mississippi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
